  "name": "Morrison COU1 CPB hemolysis — validation package (synthetic)",
  "description": "Synthetic V&V 40 UoA for CFD-based hemolysis prediction of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under cardiopulmonary bypass (CPB) conditions. The package documents validation against an in-vitro hemolysis test dataset and reports discretization, solver, and output-comparison evidence. A subtle inference-method mismatch exists in the validation layer: the cited bench comparator was operated with a porcine blood analog at 22 °C and hematocrit 36%, whereas the declared COU concerns CPB clinical operation at 32 °C with hemodiluted hematocrit in the 24–28% range. Temperature- and hematocrit-dependent viscosity differences shift the scalar stress distribution that drives the hemolysis index, so comparator applicability to the declared COU is not self-evident from the narrative.",
  "bindsRequirement": "https://uofa.net/synth/req/morrison-cou1-hemolysis-rh-lt-1",
  "bindsClaim": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/morrison-cou1-worstcase-identification",
  "bindsModel": "https://uofa.net/synth/model/morrison-cfd-centrifugal-v2",
  "bindsDataset": [
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/malinauskas-2017-benchloop-hemolysis",
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-generic-pump-geometry-v1"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-cou1-rh-index",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Relative hemolysis index (RH) agreement across 5 flow–speed operating points",
      "description": "Predicted modified index of hemolysis (MIH) was computed at the five operating points (2.5 L/min–3500 rpm; 4 L/min–3000 rpm; 4 L/min–3500 rpm; 5 L/min–3500 rpm; 6 L/min–3500 rpm) and converted to a relative hemolysis index (RH) using the Malinauskas bench loop dataset as a reference. Across the five points the CFD-predicted RH tracked the bench-reported values within ±18%, and the rank-ordering of worst-case operating points was preserved. The comparator is a well-documented, peer-reviewed bench loop experiment performed with the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, and its MIH reporting is consistent with the ASTM F1841 framework. On that basis the comparator is treated as authoritative for the RH acceptance check. Note: blood-analog viscosity conditions for the comparator loop are reported in the upstream dataset record rather than reproduced here."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-cou1-pressure-head",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Pressure–flow characteristic curve agreement",
      "description": "CFD-predicted pressure rise across the pump was compared against bench measurements at 2500, 3000, and 3500 rpm. Predictions agreed with measurements within 6.1% RMS across the operating envelope, supporting correct bulk hydraulic behavior of the solver configuration.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/malinauskas-2017-benchloop-hemolysis"
    },
    {
